04853nam a22005415i 9780822383758DE-B159720201212080620.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||201212t20022002ncu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808223837587 a10.1515/97808223837582doi  a(DE-B1597)552901  a(OCoLC)213455220  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ancucUS-NC 4aRA1231.R2bS726 2002 7aMED0390002bisacsh04a616.9/897/009771781 aStephens, Martha, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Treatment :bThe Story of Those Who Died in the Cincinnati Radiation Tests /cMartha Stephens. 1aDurham : bDuke University Press, c[2002] 4cÂ©2002  a1 online resource (372 p.) :b15 b&w photos  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface -- tPrologue -- tPart One. The Story of the Press and the Public Campaign -- t1. The First Public Knowledge of the Tests -- t2. 1994 and a Secret Drawer Reopened -- t3. The Press in Full Flower -- t4. African Americans Lost and Found -- t5. The Back Files -- t6. Testimonies -- t7. Author's Intermezzo -- tPart Two. the medical story -- t8. The Mother Without a Name -- t9. The Final Years -- t10. The Experiments Must Cease -- tPart Three. The legal story -- t11. A Civil Action -- t12. An Angry Judge -- t13. The Case Closed -- tAppendix 1. Table of Cincinnati Radiations -- tAppendix 2. Hearing Testimony of Eugene Saenger -- tNotes -- tSources -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe Treatment is the story of one tragedy of medical research that stretched over eleven years and affected the lives of hundreds of people in an Ohio city. Thirty years ago the author, then an assistant professor of English, acquired a large set of little-known medical papers at her university. These documents told a grotesque story. Cancer patients coming to the public hospital on her campus were being swept into secret experiments for the U.S. military; they were being irradiated over their whole bodies as if they were soldiers in nuclear war. Of the ninety women and men exposed to this treatment, twenty-one died within a month of their radiations.Martha Stephens's report on these deaths led to the halting of the tests, but local papers did not print her charges, and for many years people in Cincinnati had no way of knowing that lethal experiments had taken place there. In 1994 other military tests were brought to light, and a yellowed copy of Stephens's original report was delivered to a television newsroom. In Ohio, major publicity ensued-at long last-and reached around the world. Stephens uncovered the names of the victims, and a legal action was filed against thirteen researchers and their institutions. A federal judge compared the deeds of the doctors to the medical crimes of the Nazis during World War II and refused to dismiss the researchers from the suit. After many bitter disputes in court, they agreed to settle the case with the families of those they had afflicted. In 1999 a memorial plaque was raised in a yard of the hospital.Who were these doctors and why had they done as they did? Who were the people whose lives they took? Who was the reporter who could not forget the story, the young attorney who first developed the case, the judge who issued the historic ruling against the doctors? This is Stephens's moving account of all that transpired in these lives and her own during this epic battle between medicine and human rights.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 12. Dez 2020) 0aHuman experimentation in medicinezOhiozCincinnati. 0aRadiationxToxicologyxResearchzOhiozCincinnati. 7aMEDICAL / History.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDUK Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z978311071183740uhttps://doi.o